essionals approach patients who seek gender-affirming care. From genital reconstructions to hormone injections, the practice of trans medicine charts new medical ground, compelling medical professionals to plan treatments without widescale clinical trials to back them up. Relying on cultural norms and gut instincts to inform their treatment plans, shuster shows how medical providers’ lack of clinical experience and scientific research undermines their ability to interact with patients, craft treatment plans, and make medical decisions. This situation defies how providers are trained to work with patients and creates uncertainty. As providers navigate the developing knowledge surrounding the medical care of trans folk, Trans Medicine offers a rare opportunity to understand how providers make decisions while facing challenges to their expertise and, in the process, have acquired authority not only over clinical outcomes, but over gender itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGender-nonconforming peoplexMedical carezUnited States. 0aHealth services accessibilityzUnited States. 0aMedical ethicszUnited States. 0aRight to healthzUnited States. 0aTransgender peoplexMedical carezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Transgender Studies.2bisacsh  aAuthority.  aChanging Definitions of Gender.  aClinical experience.  aClinical guidelines.  aClose followers.  aCo-occurring condition.  aCollaborative decision making.  aContested medicine.  aCredibility.  aDiagnosis.  aDiagnostic criteria.  aEpistemic clashes.  aEvidence based medicine.  aEvidence.  aExperimental medicine.  aExpertise.  aFalse information.  aFlexible interpreters.  aGatekeeping.  aGender norms.  aGender.  aGut instinct.  aHealth inequalities.  aHistory of Medicine.  aInformal Evidence.  